  "summary": "Barros Basto’s 1928 Portuguese Haggadah offers a nearly continuous traditional Seder, unusually explicit table directions, a full Portuguese Maggid, blessings, and closing songs. It is valuable for Portuguese-reading and historical-cultural editions but needs language review, OCR verification, and English orientation for the current demo.",
  "sourceAssessment": {
    "voice": "Traditional, Portuguese, historical, domestic, explanatory, prayerful, and shaped by early-twentieth-century orthography and OCR.",
    "bestUses": [
      "Portuguese-language or Lusophone Jewish historical supplements",
      "Host-guide comparison of table setup and the full ritual order",
      "Traditional long-form alternatives for Maggid, symbolic foods, blessings, and closing songs"
    ],
    "beginnerRisks": [
      "The app currently promises English, so Portuguese passages cannot appear without an explicit language opt-in and checked English meaning.",
      "Historical spelling and OCR errors can make even fluent readers stumble.",
      "The source’s traditional ritual assumptions still need the project’s novice action cues."
    ],
    "politicalContext": "This 1928 Portuguese Jewish liturgy uses biblical and traditional land, Israel, temple, and Jerusalem language. It is historical-liturgical rather than modern partisan advocacy; the Jerusalem refrain remains restricted to a traditional selection without a social-justice override.",
    "creditContext": "The edition is CC0 1.0. Credit Artur Carlos de Barros Basto and the digitization where practical, and visually verify OCR-derived Portuguese before publication."
  },
